history.text: What do you think of DiCaprio's character? Do you view him as a good or bad guy at the start of the movie?
I saw him as the good guy.  I really liked him.
What did you think of how they made the inside of the dreams look?
Do you think this will be something that one day science can do?
I never seen anything like it really, i thought it was great. I doubt anything like that will exist in our time.
I wasn't surprised, were you, that the businessman wanted to use it for really bad reasons.  I can't see a good way to use this.
Corporate espionage doesn't sound like something a good guy would do, would it?
NO, you're right about that.
But otherwise, he seemed like a nice guy.  I wonder why he chose this line of work!
Did you look at the movies as a romantic film or more of an action film?
Oh, I only saw it as an action film.  I understand the bits about his...romantic parts.
Do you think Ellen Page did well as Ariadne?
What did you think about the whole airplane thing?  That was crazy.
It blew my mind that each person working in the dream was a creator of one of the dreams that they were in.  I wonder how they kept it all straight while they were dreaming.

That was an intricate plot. Would you have rather been in the dream state or the person in charge of administering
 the kick?
If I could handle it, the kick.  But i think you have to be great at lucid dreaming, and I'm not.
I thought it was neat how Fischer knew it might happen and made precautions in his head.
Wouldn't that be crazy to have to think of things like that to protect your business!!!
Not just in real life but also while you're sleeping!
Do you think the limbo really existed or it was something they were only guessing at?
It would be crazy. Getting trapped in limbo doesnt sound like fun either.
Could you imagine being in limbo for 50 years!
I cannot imagine spending 50 years in a dream!
fifty years!  what if you just couldn't wake up!?
would you be sad when you woke?
I don't think, after spending that much time dreaming, i'd really want to wake at all.  I'd do what Mal did.
Of course i would. It is like waking up tomorrow and realizing this world was just a dream state.
i never could wrap my head around the ending.  it's nice to see it explained.
Cobb had to remind her that it was all a dream, that was one heck of a wake up call!
horrible!
i would feel awful if I were in Cobb's place and it was my spouse that killed themselves thinking it would @wake@ them up!
Yeah that wasn't a very happy part. Kind of dragged my emotions on a roller coaster.
I didn't quite understand how Saito wound up in limbo, though.  Yeah, after all that, I'd have to be on antidepressants
When he joins his children, thats him giving up and calling ir quits right?
That's how I understood it.
Can't say I blame him
i'd rather pretend it was real no matter what and be with my kids
So the spinning top means he is in fact in a dream?
i wonder how he could feel okay with himself digging into people's minds for their secrets.  Yeah, if it spins indefinitely, and it never topples, then he's dreaming.
they said he ignored the result, but they didn't say what it was and i don't recall.
interesting, nonetheless.  that was one mind-blowing movie
Maybe it fell over after the camera stopped rolling :)
might have indeed.  i wonder why they chose the spinning top as his totum

uid1response.feedback: Good conversation with the other person.

uid2response.feedback: i watched the movie but found it a bit confusing, might have to watch it again.
